Document: filesystem
Path: godot/tutorials/scripting/filesystem.rst
Summary: This section explains how Godot's file system manages asset storage and access, and its role in enabling collaboration among developers.

Introduction
A file system manages how assets are stored and how they are accessed. A well-designed file system also allows multiple developers to edit the same source files and assets while collaborating. Godot stores all assets as files in its file system.
---CHUNK---
Document: FileSystem
Path: godot/tutorials/scripting/filesystem.rst
Summary: Explains how Godot's file system manages resources, sub-resources, and version control compatibility.

The file system stores resources on disk. Anything, from a script, to a scene or a PNG image is a resource to the engine. If a resource contains properties that reference other resources on disk, the paths to those resources are also included. If a resource has sub-resources that are built-in, the resource is saved in a single file together with all the bundled sub-resources. For example, a font resource is often bundled together with the font textures. The Godot file system avoids using metadata files. Existing asset managers and VCSs are better than anything we can implement, so Godot tries its best to play along with Subversion, Git, Mercurial, etc.

Example of file system contents:
/project.godot
/enemy/enemy.tscn
/enemy/enemy.gd
/enemy/enemysprite.png
/player/player.gd
---CHUNK---
Document: Filesystem and Project Configuration
Path: godot/tutorials/scripting/filesystem.rst
Summary: The project.godot file serves as the root project configuration file in Godot projects.

The project.godot file is the project description file, and it is always found at the root of the project. In fact, its location defines where the root is. This is the first file that Godot looks for when opening a project. This file contains the project configuration in plain text, using the win.ini format. Even an empty project.godot can function as a basic definition of a blank project.
---CHUNK---
Document: Filesystem Paths
Path: godot/tutorials/scripting/filesystem.rst
Summary: Godot's use of forward slashes as path delimiters and how to handle Windows file paths.

Godot only supports / as a path delimiter for portability reasons. This choice ensures compatibility across all operating systems, including Windows. When working with Windows file paths, the backslash character (\) must be replaced with a forward slash (/). For example, a Windows path like C:\project\project.godot needs to be written as C:/project/project.godot in Godot projects. This approach maintains consistent path handling regardless of the operating system being used.
---CHUNK---
Document: Filesystem  
Path: godot/tutorials/scripting/filesystem.rst  
Summary: Explains the use of the 'res://' special path in Godot for accessing project resources portably.  

Resource path  
When accessing resources, using the host OS file system layout can be cumbersome and non-portable. To solve this problem, the special path `res://` was created.  

The path `res://` will always point at the project root (where `project.godot` is located, so `res://project.godot` is always valid).  

This file system is read-write only when running the project locally from the editor. When exported or when running on different devices (such as phones or consoles, or running from DVD), the file system will become read-only and writing will no longer be permitted.
---CHUNK---
Document: Filesystem
Path: godot/tutorials/scripting/filesystem.rst
Summary: The special user:// path in Godot provides a writable location for saving game state and downloadable content across different operating systems.

The engine provides a special path called user:// that is always writable for tasks like saving game state or downloading content packs. This path resolves differently depending on the operating system the project is running on. Local path resolution details are explained in doc_data_paths.
---CHUNK---
Document: filesystem
Path: godot/tutorials/scripting/filesystem.rst
Summary: Explains the use of host file system paths in Godot, noting their platform-specific limitations and suitability for development tools.

Host file system paths can be used as an alternative, but this is not recommended for released products as these paths are not guaranteed to work across all platforms. However, using host file system paths can be useful when writing development tools in Godot.
---CHUNK---
Document: filesystem
Path: godot/tutorials/scripting/filesystem.rst
Summary: Discusses drawbacks of Godot's file system design including reference breaking and case sensitivity issues

There are some drawbacks to this file system design. The first issue is that moving assets around (renaming them or moving them from one path to another inside the project) will break existing references to these assets. These references will have to be re-defined to point at the new asset location. To avoid this, do all your move, delete and rename operations from within Godot, on the FileSystem dock. When you delete files in Godot, it will prompt you with a confirmation dialog listing all selected files and any scenes that depend on those files. Never move assets from outside Godot, or dependencies will have to be fixed manually (Godot detects this and helps you fix them anyway, but why go the hard route?).

The second issue is that under Windows and macOS, file and path names are case insensitive. If a developer working in a case insensitive host file system saves an asset as myfile.PNG but then references it as myfile.png, it will work fine on their platform, but not on other platforms, such as Linux, Android, etc. This may also apply to exported binaries, which use a compressed package to store all files. It is recommended that your team clearly define a naming convention for files when working with Godot. One fool-proof convention is to only allow lowercase file and path names.